},\n    {\n      \"answer_id\": 90,\n      \"test_id\": 9,\n      \"question_id\": 56,\n      \"answer\": \"4\",\n      \"created_at\": \"2025-11-30 22:54:58\",\n      \"test_name\": \"Reading/Writing Learning Questionnaire\",\n      \"question_text\": \"My child prefers looking at written instructions instead of only listening. ( 1 : very disagree  -  5 : very agree)\",\n      \"question_category\": \"reading\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"answer_id\": 81,\n      \"test_id\": 10,\n      \"question_id\": 62,\n      \"answer\": \"3\",\n      \"created_at\": \"2025-11-30 22:54:50\",\n      \"test_name\": \"Kinesthetic Learning Questionnaire\",\n      \"question_text\": \"My child learns better when there is hands-on activity (drawing, building, playing). ( 1 : very disagree  -  5 : very agree)\",\n      \"question_category\": \"visual\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"answer_id\": 82,\n      \"test_id\": 10,\n      \"question_id\": 63,\n      \"answer\": \"3\",\n      \"created_at\": \"2025-11-30 22:54:50\",\n      \"test_name\": \"Kinesthetic Learning Questionnaire\",\n      \"question_text\": \"My child often moves around or fidgets when learning. ( 1 : very disagree  -  5 : very agree)\",\n      \"question_category\": \"visual\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"answer_id\": 83,\n      \"test_id\": 10,\n      \"question_id\": 64,\n      \"answer\": \"3\",\n      \"created_at\": \"2025-11-30 22:54:50\",\n      \"test_name\": \"Kinesthetic Learning Questionnaire\",\n      \"question_text\": \"My child remembers things better after doing an activity. ( 1 : very disagree  -  5 : very agree)\",\n      \"question_category\": \"visual\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"answer_id\": 84,\n      \"test_id\": 10,\n      \"question_id\": 65,\n      \"answer\": \"3\",\n      \"created_at\": \"2025-11-30 22:54:50\",\n      \"test_name\": \"Kinesthetic Learning Questionnaire\",\n      \"question_text\": \"My child likes to touch and explore objects when they are curious. ( 1 : very disagree  -  5 : very agree)\",\n      \"question_category\": \"visual\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"answer_id\": 85,\n      \"test_id\": 10,\n      \"question_id\": 66,\n      \"answer\": \"3\",\n      \"created_at\": \"2025-11-30 22:54:50\",\n      \"test_name\": \"Kinesthetic Learning Questionnaire\",\n      \"question_text\": \"My child finds it hard to sit still for a long time during quiet learning. ( 1 : very disagree  -  5 : very agree)\",\n      \"question_category\": \"visual\"\n    }\n  ]\n}', '<h5>Learning Style Summary</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>Visual          : Strong, as they consistently prefer images, videos, and visual materials.</li>\n<li>Auditory        : Moderate, as they enjoy discussions and sound-based games.</li>\n<li>Reading/Writing : Moderate, as they show interest in written words and early literacy.</li>\n<li>Kinesthetic     : Weak, as hands-on activities are not their primary learning preference.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h5>Main Learning Style</h5>\n<p>Your child is primarily a visual learner, with developing strengths in auditory and early reading/writing styles.</p>\n\n<h6>Tips for Parents</h6>\n<ul>\n<li>Use plenty of pictures, videos, and visual aids when teaching new things.</li>\n<li>Encourage discussions and ask questions to help your child process information.</li>\n<li>Point out words and labels in books and daily life to nurture early reading skills.</li>\n</ul>', '2025-11-30 15:44:11', '2025-11-30 15:44:11'),
(24, 15, 'preschool', '[{\"id\": 19, \"child_id\": 15, \"domain\": \"Social/Emotional Milestones\", \"description\": \"Always not happy\", \"date\": \"2025-02-01\", \"date_str\": \"2025-02\", \"age_months\": 24}, {\"id\": 18, \"child_id\": 15, \"domain\": \"Language/Communication\", \"description\": \"Can read story book\", \"date\": \"2025-01-01\", \"date_str\": \"2025-01\", \"age_months\": 23}]', '<p><strong>Child\'s Name:</strong> Chen</p>\n<p><strong>Age for Assessment:</strong> 24 months (2 years old)</p>\n\n<h3>Developmental Summary:</h3>\n\n<h4>Areas that are age-appropriate:</h4>\n<p>Based on the limited provided data, specific age-appropriate milestones cannot be confirmed for most developmental domains, such as Cognitive and Movement/Physical Development.</p>\n\n<h4>Areas that are delayed:</h4>\n<ul>\n    <li><strong>Social/Emotional:</strong> The observation that Chen is \"Always not happy (at 24 months)\" is a significant concern. This indicates a potential delay or atypical pattern in social-emotional development, as children at this age typically express a broader range of emotions and begin to engage in more complex social interactions.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Areas that are advanced for the child\'s age:</h4>\n<ul>\n    <li><strong>Language/Communication:</strong> Chen\'s ability to \"Can read story book (at 23 months)\" is remarkably advanced. Reading full storybooks is typically a skill developed much later, often between 5 to 6 years of age, far exceeding the expected language milestones for a 2-year-old who would typically be pointing to pictures in books and forming simple sentences.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Overall, Chen exhibits significantly advanced language and literacy skills, while also showing a notable concern in his social-emotional well-being that warrants further evaluation.</p>', '2025-12-01 09:41:56', '2025-12-01 09:42:46'),
(26, 15, 'tutoring', '{\n  \"learning\": \"<h5>Learning Style Summary</h5>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Visual : Strong. Your child really enjoys learning through videos and cartoons.</li>\\n<li>Auditory : Weak. Your child shows a clear preference for less verbal interaction.</li>\\n<li>Reading/Writing : Weak. Your child doesn\'t seem to engage much with written words or text yet.</li>\\n<li>Kinesthetic : Moderate. Your child often moves around or fidgets, suggesting some hands-on preference.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h5>Main Learning Style</h5>\\n<p>Your child primarily learns visually, with some moderate kinesthetic (hands-on) tendencies.</p>\\n\\n<h6>Tips for Parents</h6>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Use lots of pictures, videos, and visual aids to introduce new ideas and concepts.</li>\\n<li>Encourage hands-on activities like building, drawing, or exploring objects to support their learning.</li>\\n<li>Remember they might prefer to show you rather than tell you, so offer visual cues and demonstrations.</li>\\n</ul>\",\n  \"preschool\": \"<p><strong>Child\'s Name:</strong> Chen</p>\\n<p><strong>Age for Assessment:</strong> 24 months (2 years old)</p>\\n\\n<h3>Developmental Summary:</h3>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are age-appropriate:</h4>\\n<p>Based on the limited provided data, specific age-appropriate milestones cannot be confirmed for most developmental domains, such as Cognitive and Movement/Physical Development.</p>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are delayed:</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Social/Emotional:</strong> The observation that Chen is \\\"Always not happy (at 24 months)\\\" is a significant concern. This indicates a potential delay or atypical pattern in social-emotional development, as children at this age typically express a broader range of emotions and begin to engage in more complex social interactions.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are advanced for the child\'s age:</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Language/Communication:</strong> Chen\'s ability to \\\"Can read story book (at 23 months)\\\" is remarkably advanced. Reading full storybooks is typically a skill developed much later, often between 5 to 6 years of age, far exceeding the expected language milestones for a 2-year-old who would typically be pointing to pictures in books and forming simple sentences.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<p>Overall, Chen exhibits significantly advanced language and literacy skills, while also showing a notable concern in his social-emotional well-being that warrants further evaluation.</p>\"\n}', '<h3>1. Potential Weak Areas</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Social-Emotional Development:</strong> There\'s a significant concern regarding Chen\'s consistent unhappiness and potential difficulties in expressing emotions and engaging in positive social interactions, which is crucial for a nursery-aged child.</li>\n  <li><strong>Auditory Engagement and Expressive Communication:</strong> Chen\'s preference for less verbal interaction and a weak auditory learning style suggest he may struggle with purely verbal instructions or discussions, and might benefit from more support in expressing his thoughts and feelings verbally.</li>\n  <li><strong>Fine Motor Skills for Writing:</strong> While Chen exhibits exceptionally advanced reading abilities, his reported disengagement with written words or text might indicate a need to develop foundational fine motor skills and pre-writing readiness to bridge this gap.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2. Recommended Focus Areas</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Social-Emotional Learning (SEL):</strong> Prioritizing activities that help Chen understand, identify, and express his emotions, as well as develop empathy and positive social interaction skills.</li>\n  <li><strong>Visual and Kinesthetic Communication:</strong> Supporting Chen in communicating his needs and emotions through visual cues and hands-on activities, given his advanced visual processing and moderate kinesthetic preference.</li>\n  <li><strong>Pre-Writing and Creative Expression:</strong> Engaging in activities that strengthen fine motor control and provide an outlet for creative expression, which can also tie into emotional processing.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3. Personalized Activities</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Emotion Detective Play:</strong> Use picture cards or visual charts depicting various emotions. Encourage Chen to identify emotions, mimic them, and discuss what might make someone feel that way (visual, kinesthetic, social-emotional).</li>\n  <li><strong>Role-Playing with Puppets/Dolls:</strong> Create simple scenarios using puppets or toy figures to act out social situations, practicing greetings, sharing, and expressing feelings. This provides a safe, hands-on way to explore interactions (kinesthetic, visual, social-emotional).</li>\n  <li><strong>Visual Story Creation:</strong> Encourage Chen to draw or create simple visual stories (using stickers, cut-outs, or digital drawing apps) about characters experiencing different feelings or social events. He can then \"read\" his own visual narrative, linking his advanced reading to creative expression (visual, kinesthetic, reading, social-emotional).</li>\n  <li><strong>Sensory Play & Art for Expression:</strong> Engage in open-ended sensory activities like play-doh, sand play, or painting with large brushes. Encourage him to describe what he\'s creating or how the textures feel, indirectly linking sensations to emotions (kinesthetic, visual, fine motor).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4. Recommended Learning Materials</h3>\n<p>Here are specific products to support Chen\'s learning:</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Parent Action Plan:</strong> Your primary focus should be on nurturing Chen\'s emotional well-being and helping him develop robust social-emotional skills through visual and hands-on play. Leverage his extraordinary reading ability by providing books that support emotional understanding, and gently encourage fine motor development for future writing skills.</p>', '2025-12-01 09:46:20', '2025-12-01 14:16:06');
