(27, 15, 'tutoring', '{\n  \"learning\": \"<h5>Learning Style Summary</h5>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Visual          : Strong - Your child loves watching videos and cartoons daily.</li>\\n<li>Auditory        : Weak - We don\'t have specific information about this style.</li>\\n<li>Reading/Writing : Weak - We don\'t have specific information about this style.</li>\\n<li>Kinesthetic     : Moderate - Your child shows some tendency to move and fidget, and enjoys hands-on activities sometimes.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h5>Main Learning Style</h5>\\n<p>Your child appears to be a primarily Visual learner with some Kinesthetic tendencies.</p>\\n\\n<h6>Tips for Parents</h6>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Use colorful books with lots of pictures, educational videos, and visual aids when teaching new concepts.</li>\\n<li>Incorporate movement and hands-on play, such as building with blocks or drawing, into learning time.</li>\\n<li>Encourage safe exploration of objects and allow your child to touch and feel things they are curious about.</li>\\n</ul>\",\n  \"preschool\": \"<p><strong>Child\'s Name:</strong> Chen</p>\\n<p><strong>Age for Assessment:</strong> 24 months (2 years old)</p>\\n\\n<h3>Developmental Summary:</h3>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are age-appropriate:</h4>\\n<p>Based on the limited provided data, specific age-appropriate milestones cannot be confirmed for most developmental domains, such as Cognitive and Movement/Physical Development.</p>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are delayed:</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Social/Emotional:</strong> The observation that Chen is \\\"Always not happy (at 24 months)\\\" is a significant concern. This indicates a potential delay or atypical pattern in social-emotional development, as children at this age typically express a broader range of emotions and begin to engage in more complex social interactions.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are advanced for the child\'s age:</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Language/Communication:</strong> Chen\'s ability to \\\"Can read story book (at 23 months)\\\" is remarkably advanced. Reading full storybooks is typically a skill developed much later, often between 5 to 6 years of age, far exceeding the expected language milestones for a 2-year-old who would typically be pointing to pictures in books and forming simple sentences.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<p>Overall, Chen exhibits significantly advanced language and literacy skills, while also showing a notable concern in his social-emotional well-being that warrants further evaluation.</p>\"\n}', '<h3>1. Potential Weak Areas</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Social-Emotional Development:</strong> The observation that Chen was \"always not happy\" at 24 months is a significant concern. At 3 years old, children are developing a wider range of emotions and social skills, including empathy, sharing, and cooperative play. Chen needs focused support to understand, express, and manage his emotions, and to engage in positive social interactions.</li>\n  <li><strong>Emotional Regulation and Expression:</strong> Related to the above, Chen may benefit from learning healthy strategies to identify and communicate his feelings, moving beyond persistent unhappiness.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2. Recommended Focus Areas</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Social-Emotional Learning (SEL):</strong> This should be the primary focus, aiming to build emotional literacy, self-awareness, self-management, and social awareness.</li>\n  <li><strong>Play-Based Social Skills:</strong> Encouraging structured and unstructured play that promotes interaction, sharing, turn-taking, and understanding social cues.</li>\n  <li><strong>Creative Emotional Expression:</strong> Utilizing art, music, or imaginative play as outlets for processing and expressing feelings in a safe and constructive manner.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3. Personalized Activities</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Emotion Recognition Games:</strong> Use picture cards or videos depicting various facial expressions and body language. Ask Chen to identify the emotion and discuss what might make someone feel that way, leveraging his strong visual learning style and advanced literacy.</li>\n  <li><strong>Interactive Storytelling with Puppets/Characters:</strong> Create simple puppet shows or use action figures to act out social scenarios (e.g., sharing, making a friend, dealing with frustration). Encourage Chen to participate, predict outcomes, or suggest solutions, tapping into his kinesthetic and visual preferences.</li>\n  <li><strong>\"My Feelings\" Drawing/Building:</strong> Provide art supplies or blocks and encourage Chen to draw or build something that represents how he feels, or how a character in a story might feel. This provides a visual and kinesthetic outlet for emotional expression.</li>\n  <li><strong>\"Role-Play and Pretend Play Corners\":</strong> Set up designated areas with props (e.g., a \"doctor\'s office,\" \"grocery store,\" or \"home\") to encourage imaginative role-play with an adult or another child, fostering social interaction and understanding of different roles and emotions.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4. Recommended Learning Materials</h3>\n<p>Here are specific products to support Chen\'s learning:</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Parent Action Plan:</strong> Parents should prioritize creating a highly supportive and engaging environment focused on Chen\'s social-emotional development. Leverage his strong visual learning and advanced literacy by using books, visual aids, and imaginative play to help him identify, understand, and express his emotions, and to practice social interactions with gentle guidance.</p>', '2025-12-01 09:46:28', '2025-12-01 09:46:28'),
