 observation that Chen is \\\"Always not happy (at 24 months)\\\" is a significant concern. This indicates a potential delay or atypical pattern in social-emotional development, as children at this age typically express a broader range of emotions and begin to engage in more complex social interactions.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h4>Areas that are advanced for the child\'s age:</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Language/Communication:</strong> Chen\'s ability to \\\"Can read story book (at 23 months)\\\" is remarkably advanced. Reading full storybooks is typically a skill developed much later, often between 5 to 6 years of age, far exceeding the expected language milestones for a 2-year-old who would typically be pointing to pictures in books and forming simple sentences.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<p>Overall, Chen exhibits significantly advanced language and literacy skills, while also showing a notable concern in his social-emotional well-being that warrants further evaluation.</p>\", \"tutoring_result\": \"<h3>1. Potential Weak Areas</h3>\\n<ul>\\n  <li><strong>Social-Emotional Development:</strong> There\'s a significant concern regarding Chen\'s consistent unhappiness and potential difficulties in expressing emotions and engaging in positive social interactions, which is crucial for a nursery-aged child.</li>\\n  <li><strong>Auditory Engagement and Expressive Communication:</strong> Chen\'s preference for less verbal interaction and a weak auditory learning style suggest he may struggle with purely verbal instructions or discussions, and might benefit from more support in expressing his thoughts and feelings verbally.</li>\\n  <li><strong>Fine Motor Skills for Writing:</strong> While Chen exhibits exceptionally advanced reading abilities, his reported disengagement with written words or text might indicate a need to develop foundational fine motor skills and pre-writing readiness to bridge this gap.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>2. Recommended Focus Areas</h3>\\n<ul>\\n  <li><strong>Social-Emotional Learning (SEL):</strong> Prioritizing activities that help Chen understand, identify, and express his emotions, as well as develop empathy and positive social interaction skills.</li>\\n  <li><strong>Visual and Kinesthetic Communication:</strong> Supporting Chen in communicating his needs and emotions through visual cues and hands-on activities, given his advanced visual processing and moderate kinesthetic preference.</li>\\n  <li><strong>Pre-Writing and Creative Expression:</strong> Engaging in activities that strengthen fine motor control and provide an outlet for creative expression, which can also tie into emotional processing.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>3. Personalized Activities</h3>\\n<ul>\\n  <li><strong>Emotion Detective Play:</strong> Use picture cards or visual charts depicting various emotions. Encourage Chen to identify emotions, mimic them, and discuss what might make someone feel that way (visual, kinesthetic, social-emotional).</li>\\n  <li><strong>Role-Playing with Puppets/Dolls:</strong> Create simple scenarios using puppets or toy figures to act out social situations, practicing greetings, sharing, and expressing feelings. This provides a safe, hands-on way to explore interactions (kinesthetic, visual, social-emotional).</li>\\n  <li><strong>Visual Story Creation:</strong> Encourage Chen to draw or create simple visual stories (using stickers, cut-outs, or digital drawing apps) about characters experiencing different feelings or social events. He can then \\\"read\\\" his own visual narrative, linking his advanced reading to creative expression (visual, kinesthetic, reading, social-emotional).</li>\\n  <li><strong>Sensory Play & Art for Expression:</strong> Engage in open-ended sensory activities like play-doh, sand play, or painting with large brushes. Encourage him to describe what he\'s creating or how the textures feel, indirectly linking sensations to emotions (kinesthetic, visual, fine motor).</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>4. Recommended Learning Materials</h3>\\n<p>Here are specific products to support Chen\'s learning:</p>\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n<p><strong>Parent Action Plan:</strong> Your primary focus should be on nurturing Chen\'s emotional well-being and helping him develop robust social-emotional skills through visual and hands-on play. Leverage his extraordinary reading ability by providing books that support emotional understanding, and gently encourage fine motor development for future writing skills.</p>\"}', '<h3>Learning Plan Summary</h3>\n<p>Dear Parents, this week\'s plan for Chen is designed to beautifully blend his amazing ability to learn visually and his love for hands-on activities. We\'ll focus on helping him explore and express his wonderful feelings, while also nurturing his communication skills in fun and engaging ways. Your active participation will truly make a difference in helping Chen blossom emotionally and creatively!</p>\n\n<h3>Weekly Action Plan</h3>\n<table class=\"table table-striped\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr><th>Day</th><th>Recommended Activities</th></tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Day 1</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Emotion Detective Play (15 mins):</strong> Use picture cards or visual charts showing different emotions (happy, sad, excited, angry). Point to each face and gently ask, \"How do you think this person feels?\" Encourage Chen to mimic the faces.</li>\n          <li><strong>Feeling Story Time (15-20 mins):</strong> Read a storybook that features characters experiencing various emotions. Pause to ask, \"How do you think the character feels now?\" Point to the pictures for clues.</li>\n          <li><strong>\"My Happy Place\" Drawing (15 mins):</strong> Provide paper and crayons. Ask Chen to draw something that makes him feel happy. This encourages visual expression of feelings.</li>\n        </ul>\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Day 2</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Puppet Play for Sharing (15-20 mins):</strong> Use hand puppets or stuffed animals to act out a simple scenario about sharing toys or saying \"hello.\" Let Chen join in the play, guiding him through simple interactions.</li>\n          <li><strong>Play-Doh Emotion Faces (15 mins):</strong> Encourage Chen to use Play-Doh to create different emotion faces (e.g., a happy face, a surprised face). This is a wonderful hands-on way to explore feelings and strengthen fine motor skills.</li>\n          <li><strong>Visual Language Exploration (15 mins):</strong> Watch a short, engaging educational video in Chinese or Malay that uses lots of clear visuals and actions (e.g., about animals or colours).</li>\n        </ul>\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Day 3</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>\"How Do I Feel?\" Mirror Time (10 mins):</strong> Sit with Chen in front of a mirror. Make different emotional faces (happy, sad, silly) and encourage him to copy you. Name each emotion as you make the face.</li>\n          <li><strong>Sensory Bin Exploration (20 mins):</strong> Set up a sensory bin with rice, beans, or water and some small cups/scoops. Encourage free play, describing what you both see and feel. This is great for kinesthetic learning and can be calming.</li>\n          <li><strong>Big Shape Tracing (15 mins):</strong> Use large paper and thick crayons or markers. Draw big circles, squares, or lines and encourage Chen to trace over them. This is a gentle introduction to pre-writing skills.</li>\n        </ul>\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Day 4</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Emotion Matching Game (15 mins):</strong> Print two sets of simple emotion cards. Play a visual memory or matching game to help Chen recognise and name different feelings.</li>\n          <li><strong>\"What Makes Me Feel...\" Collage (20 mins):</strong> Provide magazines, child-safe scissors, and glue. Help Chen cut out pictures of things that make him feel happy, excited, or calm, and glue them onto a piece of paper.</li>\n          <li><strong>Read & Point Story (15 mins):</strong> Choose an English storybook with vibrant pictures. Instead of just reading, ask Chen to point out specific objects or characters on each page, using simple language.</li>\n        </ul>\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Day 5</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Visual Story Creation (20 mins):</strong> Use stickers, cut-outs, or simple drawings to create a short \"visual story\" together. It could be about a character having a happy day or feeling a little shy, providing an outlet for creative expression.</li>\n          <li><strong>Outdoor \"Happy Hunt\" (20 mins):</strong> Go for a walk outside. Point out things that might make people feel happy (e.g., a colourful flower, a chirping bird, a sunny sky). Encourage Chen to share what makes him happy too.</li>\n          <li><strong>Musical Movement & Emotion (15 mins):</strong> Play different types of music (fast, slow, cheerful, calm). Encourage Chen to move his body in ways that match the music, and talk about how the music makes him feel.</li>\n        </ul>\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>Long-Term Strategy</h3>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Daily \"Feeling Check-in\":</strong> Make it a habit to ask Chen how he\'s feeling each day, using visual cues like an emotion chart if verbal expression is challenging.</li>\n  <li><strong>Continue Visual & Hands-on Learning:</strong> Always introduce new ideas through pictures, videos, and objects that Chen can touch and explore, aligning with his strong visual and kinesthetic preferences.</li>\n  <li><strong>Gentle Pre-Writing Exploration:</strong> Keep fine motor activities fun and pressure-free. Focus on drawing, scribbling, and sensory play that strengthens hand muscles, rather than formal writing.</li>\n  <li><strong>Empathetic Storytelling:</strong> Regularly read books and watch age-appropriate shows that feature characters navigating social situations and expressing a range of emotions.</li>\n  <li><strong>Nurture Expressive Communication:</strong> Encourage Chen to communicate his thoughts and feelings through his drawings, actions, and later, simple words, validating every attempt he makes.</li>\n</ul>', '2025-12-01 09:48:31', '2025-12-01 14:19:16'),
